I am a very experienced Ramen eater ... Ivan, Hide Chan, Terrakawa, Menkui Tei, Ippudo ... etc ... I really wanted to like Makamura, due to the proximity of the restaurant to my apt ... but the flavors were flat and portions small for the price ... all in all pretty disappointing ramen ...

First of all I just want to start off by saying this. This was THE worst bowl of curry chicken ramen I’ve ever had in my life. For god’s sake I make better ramen at home! For starters the chicken had no type of flavor, only flavor it had was the taste of the grill. The broth which they said in the description was supposed to be a spicy curry, turned out to be watery curry with no spice and no FLAVOR. The pork I will say this, was very flavorful and delicious you guys get a thumbs up for that. The disrespect of this entire meal had to be the noodles and the price tag. The noodles were mediocre at best and the price at 23$ I could’ve gotten two bowls of better curry ramen at Naruto ramen! Only reason I gave this place a shot was because my coworker was buying lunch. Needless to say we ended up throwing out our food, it was just that bad.
This place is super delicious

Highly recommend. I’ve tried four different ramens here, and each one has had completely different flavor profiles and characteristics, delivering a truly diverse variety of (wonderfully delicious) ramen options unlike any of the many, many others ramen places I’ve tried in the city.  Location is pretty small, but they do a good job of serving/seating people pretty quickly, and the atmosphere is enjoyably cozy. Pro tip: join the Yelp waitlist ahead of going.  Love their custom Nakamura ramen bowls featuring drawings of famous NYC sites. The ramen spoons are also more ergonomic than some other ramen places, making for easy portioning & sipping.
Small intimate location. Has a nice variety of different broths and toppings. You can do yelp waitlist to help with the wait time since there’s probably going to be an hour wait on weekends

When we were in NYC last summer we researched a lot what the best ramen shop is and ultimately narrowed it down to two, both in LES. For no particular reason we decided to go with Nakamura. The place is tiny, yet cosy. No toilet or option to wash your hands, which wasn't that amazing. Menu is short, but absolutely enough. We got shiso fries as a starter (nice!) and the tontoro pork ramen.The ajitsuke tamago doesn't come with the ramen if you don't order it extra. We did and it was perfectly cooked and marinated. Broth was velvety, rich and super delicious, noodles were nice! The best ramen I have tried so far (however I haven't been to Japan!). I will definitely return!

This place is my preferred one. I go to many restaurants but to this one I go the most. The team is very helpful and the cuisine they cook is so yummy. I never decline to have a nice meal here. I recommend this place with pleasure.

Came here to eat, asked for the bathroom so i could wash my hands before eating and there wasn’t one? They told me to go to all the way to Essex Market... what type of restaurant doesn’t have a bathroom?  Needless to say, I left.

I got the chicken curry ramen and my wife got the Jidori chicken based broth ramen. I really liked that they use chunks of grilled chicken instead of the circular chicken breast slices that most other ramen places use. We both felt that the broths were a bit watered down, however, they didnt really pack that umami/heavy punch that ramen usually has and so it was a bit of a letdown. Also they put tons and tons of sprouts into the ramen which took away from the experience as well. They were very nice and attentive staff and we got seated right away which was awesome. We thought overall the prices for the ramen were too high...

Came here for lunch at 12pm, place is empty and immediately greeted by the waitress, friendly and attentive, she's new. This place is famous for the tsukemen (limited availability) by chef Nakamura. We ordered pulled pork tsukemen and torigara ramen and fried shishito.  Shishito is perfect, lightly fried, not too oily and the salt is just enough for the flavor. Fresh, and it doesnt overly hit the spicy unbearable level. Tsukemen noodle is a tad too soft to my liking, its not al dente, and cold (winter i guess?). The pulled pork broth is overly salty if consumed by its own, but when mixed, it paired up nicely. Torigara ramen is a clear soup base, with I'd say has more of a chinese flavor to it rather than japanese (perhaps of the spices and ingredients). Noodle is also a tad on the softer side.  First time trying tsukemen, i still prefer the classic style ramen where my noodle is firm and soaked in the goodness of broth. Attentive and friendly service, cozy and relaxing place. Though they messed up my order, ordered the lunch size, and when the bill came it shows up the normal price.

Loved this ramen shop! Came here for a quick dinner, and couldn't have left happier. I ordered the truffle umami fries and the tontoro ramen— both were delicious! The fries are pretty much like fancy seasoned McDonald's fries, in the best way possible. The broth was thick and rich, and soooo fragrant from the sesame oil. The noodles were thick and chewy! I only wish I ordered extra noodles, it was that good!!
Awesome little joint. Tontoro broth was really creamy and rich.

We like the ramen at Nakamura. Very satisfying on a cold New York evening. Luckily, we didn't have to wait long for a table because it wasn't completely slammed. I thought the chicken wings were very strange, more like a pile of bones that had been fried. It made me wonder where the rest of the wings went. They have another place next door that serves a drier dish no broth ramen - mazemen and there was a bit of a line there. The menu had some crossover items so you could also get a couple of the mazemen options without having to wait on line next door. The service was Swift and efficient.

To start off, I was excited to come try this restaurant with my folks. We had lunch here on a weekday around 1pm. It wasn't crowded. There were tables so we were seated promptly.  Our waiter came to take our order within a minute but my parents were still looking at the menu. Whoa..slow your roll boy!  We ordered after a few minutes and while we were waiting for our ramen, the waiter was on his phone the entire time. Not very professional.  Our food came and in all honesty it was nothing to write home about.  Jidori chicken ramen Chicken was dry and overcooked. Too much bean sprouts in the noodle and not much else. Flavor was average at best. Noodle was not al dente bordering on the mushy side. I paid an extra $2 for the egg which was not that tasty.  Tontoro ramen My parents had that. Mom said it was too salty. I tried it and indeed it was. They weren't didn't particularly enjoy the paper thin slice of pork either.  For what they charge, I would expect something better. Disappointing..but not as appalling as what I saw next...  While we were still waiting for our food, the couple next to us asked for the check. The waiter gave it to them and they charged it with their credit card. They must have been japanese customers from out of town because the entire time they were speaking japanese. When they got up to leave, the waiter rudely said YOU DIDN'T TIP ME in front of all the patrons.!!! Not acceptable on any level! If you didn't get tipped, you should speak with them in private perhaps outside NOT IN FRONT OF ALL THE CUSTOMERS. My folks and I clearly heard him say it. The Japanese customers were clearly taken aback and didn't really understand what he was saying so he said it again and then they finally realized that he wanted a tip. Ok I get it..maybe the out of towners forgot but the waiter totally EMBARRASSED them and made them look a fool in front of everyone in the restaurant. Not cool at all. And then the customer tipped him and hurriedly left. The waiter looks at me in disbelief and I say well they don't tip in Asia..and he said well this is AMERICA. I get it. But there's really no need to be so rude about it. Maybe they didn't like your service or lack of service. And then he proceeds to tell me that the Asians and Europeans tend to do this. HELLO! I'm Asian and frankly speaking I'm thinking about whether or not I should tip you now that you're so outright rude!!  **a quick scan of the space and there was not one japanese staff there whether it was front of house or in the kitchen. Hmmm maybe that's why!  One done. None shoulda gone.

Nothing disappointed especially the clean layered and complex flavored broth.  I like the way the pork is presented.  Server was right, I’ve already started thinking about the next bowl.

Dang, I ordered the wrong ramen. Got the Shaki Shaki Spicy Ramen. Would not recommend. OVERLOADED with bean sprouts, as you can see from the picture. What I didn’t realize was that it didn’t come with any meat at all. It was just noodles and vegetables with some strange non-ramen-like broth. Very below average and definitely not worth the $20 I spent. Water tasted like tap water and wasn’t even cold.  Service was kinda bad. Super small place with limited seating on a Saturday evening ~7:30 pm. I waited almost 30 minutes for a seat for 1.  Overall, I should’ve listened to the other reviews and gotten the Torigara ramen. Or even the Tontoro Pork would’ve been better. Ruined my dinner with the Shaki Shaki.

I have been comming here since they opened in 2016. The portions of only getting slimmer and Everytime I go, I always have a new server. They don't remember you, they only give smaller portions, and they just want you to hurry up and get the next person in the seat.

Try the torigara if it’s your first time— favorite bowl of ramen in nyc. The broth is clean and flavorful without being fatty/greasy. It’ll leave you feeling refreshed rather than weighed down. The meat and egg are cooked perfectly and the noodles have the right amount of spring. Awesome place. The specials are usually great too— if there is tsukemen available, get it!

This place felt like someones home in the best possible way. It's chefs and support staff were humble, polite and warm. The food spoke for itself. Some of the best flavors I've had in a bowl of ramen anywhere. Top marks in every category for me. I would reccomend anyone to go see for themselves.

Though I have to say, it was a tad bit pricey for two bite-sized pieces but, then again, this is uni we're talking about which is normally pricey. The location of the restaurant seemed kind of like a hole-in-the-wall to me because of how small and slightly out-of-the-way it is. But, despite that, it felt cozy to me. Putting that aside, the food is definitely good and the price is typical of ramen in the city. Definitely give it a try if you're in the area. The first time I went I got the signature bowl which has a great light & delicious umami flavor 2nd time I got the tontoro which was the creamiest tonkatsu broth without being to heavy & fatty like other ones I’ve had. Went here for a 3rd time a few months ago in fall of 2018 & got shaki shaki spicy ramen & it wasn’t any where near as good as it was the other 2 times I was there this bowl had very little flavor & wasn’t all that spicy the noodles weren’t very good either after this 3rd time I don’t know if I’ll be back again.

Ramen was 5-Star but the Yuzu wings were not that good to me so that overall I gave them 4-Star.  2018-09-05 Wed 9:28-10:04pm 《Torigara Ramen 🍜 & Yuzu Wings at Nakamura Ramen in Manhattan, New York》It was great to have a chance to try this good rating ramen shop tonight. It was easy to find a Free street parking on weekdays evening. $14 Torigara Ramen 🍜 鶏がらラーメン / 雞湯拉麵 I love Torigara (light & clean chicken broth). The Torigara soup was perfect to me with light soy sauce. I was happy to have the chashu pork that was fixed and warmed when it was served. The extra order of marinated egg $2 tasted perfect 👌🏻 and not too salty. $10 Yuzu Wings 柚子の手羽先 雞翼/雞翅 This dish looks like coming with 10 wings. Actually each wing was cut in half so that total were 5 wings. The wings were deep fried and then topped with housemade Yuzu sauce. Mmm.... As an appetizer, this dish was okay to me but I was not that excited when I was having them. The sauce was like American yuzu sauce and it was a bit salty and too sweet to me. I will go back there for trying another kind of Ramen menu next time instead of wings. Service: My orders were down in 10 minuets that was great. Two guys at the kitchen and the only waitress were not Japanese. Service was okay 👌🏻 as American style. Don’t expect to hear “thank you” when you step out this ramen shop. Remember that here is America. I like that they use an electronic pad for letting me pay tips and sign. I got my receipt by email electronically. Size of the ramen shop: only 20 seats with 8 small tables (one table for 2 people) and 4 counter seats. Restroom: very clean ! I didn’t expect too much but I was surprised to see that clean restroom when I opened the door.

Great ramen!!! I love how their tonkotsu is paired with the chewy noodle. Broth is on the thick and salty side. Their shiso fries are heavenly. Staffs are friendly and knowledgable. Only small minus is the size of the place. There are literally enough seats for less than 20 people...
Pretty damn good ramen. Cant wait to go back again

The best bowl of Ramen that I've ever had. The broth was creamy and rich. Combine that with thick chewy noodles, hot oil and that awesome ajitama egg and you get an explosion of flavor in your mouth. Nakamura is a small but wonderful restaurant on Delancey Street. I did think it was strange that there was an extra cost to add boiled egg to the ramen, as I have typically had that included in the base. There is also an option for extra noodles, which we saw come in handy for a fellow patron who ordered the larger bowl, and wanted to finish the remaining broth with more noodles.  The restaurant is small, so capacity is quite low, which might explain the wait some reviewers mentioned.  The staff is friendly, and the service is really nice without being overbearing. Overall, good place.

This tiny and wonderfully cozy little ramen shop will be perfect on a cold day. It will be perfect on a hot boiling day too (you just need to get a bowl of cold noodles).  The flavor is wonderful, the decor is inviting, the kitchen is busy and hot and ramen here is made with a strong passion and it shows not only in the kitchen but the waitstaff as well.  Highly recommended, pictured is the XO Miso (vegan on the menu, vegetarian because of the added ajitama egg). Not pictured but also highly recommended is the Cauliflower / Crimini Sautee appetizer.
